@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node About "About the AVD"
The Agressive VirusDetector. or just AVD, is a small tool for checking the
computer for the presence of virusses. As the name already implies: The
AVD just detects the virusses. For the removal other applications exist
in the public domain. The benefit of the AVD is it size (very small) and
the time it takes to execute (almost none).

The detection uses this principle: When a virus wants to spread, it must
infiltrate the operating system. To hide this to the user it must make
itself invisible: this is called stealth. The AVD tries to find all code
trying to be invisible using stealth techniques. Also it tries to find
all kinds of system infiltration.
The problem is that some older tools and some hardware devellopers use
a sort of system infiltration to add the tool ot hardware component. In
order to stop the false alarms this causes, tests can be switched off.

@{i}What is the philosophy behind AVD?@{ui}

The AVD was never meant as a complete protection on itself! It is more
an addition. By placing the AVD in the S:StartUp-Sequence or the 
S:User-Startup the computer is tested very boot. Now the major part
of virusses will be found. The only way to be complete safe is to use
a scanner to check (with fixed intervals) your complete harddisk.
All this may be seen in the way it works with the maintainance of an
automobile: Checking the oil does never take away the need for the
10.000 km check. But it can avoid a lot of trouble!

@{i}What is the benefit of the AVD?@{ui}

By placing the AVD in the S:StartUp-Sequence or the S:User-Startup the
system is checked every boot. Since the AVD is very small and execution
doesn't take much time you don't lose anything, but gain in security.
Another benefit of the small size is that the AVD fits easily on a floppy
disk. Users without harddisk can use their favourite WorkBench disk!
Also the AVD doesn't have any system requirement. Type of processor or
chipset are unimportant.
The only requirement is a little knowledge of the operating system to
react on the warnings given by AVD.

Without showing off I am able to say that the AVD detects more @{"stealth" LINK Stealth }
techniques compared to the viruskillers I tested. Most viruskillers
depend on the recognition of known virusses.

@{i}How many virusses are known by this AVD thing?@{ui}

Hmm. To a question like this I cannot give any answer. This since the
viruswriting idiots outhere are still creating code which instantly
will be detected by the AVD... The AVD doesn't recognise by name, it
only detects that shit is thrown in the direction of the van...

@{i}On what systems is it tested?@{ui}

The AVD is tested and used on different systems. My own system went from
OS1.3 via OS2.0 onto OS3.0. A list showing systems on which the AVD 
worked without problems:

System		O.S.	CHIPMEM	FASTMEM	Extra

A500		1.3	512kB	2.5MB	52MB SCSI HD
A500		1.3	1MB	2MB	52MB SCSI HD
A500		2.0	512kB	2.5MB	52MB SCSI HD
A500		2.0	1MB	2MB	52MB SCSI HD
A1200		3.0	2MB
A1200		3.0	2MB	4MB	68030 en 68882 op 40MHz
A4000		3.0	2MB	4MB	68882 op 25MHz
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node Stealth "Stealth checking..."
Personally I find it challenging to find ways to infiltrate the system
in ways the AVD wouldn't detect. Offcourse I do not use this information
to create virusses. No. I use it to improve the AVD. friends of me are
also trying to find ways to fool the AVD. (They think that if they can't
fool me, they have to fool the AVD... And thats not simple either...)

To test the new way found, I always create a test application. Instead
of infecting new disks these applications show some color flashes on the
screen meaning "normally this would be dangerous".
After that I change the AVD to make it detecting this kind of stealth and
release a new AVD version.

Sometimes I test other viruskillers to check if they are able to detect
the new way of infiltration I invented. Next to never other viruskillers
detect my way of infiltration.

Thus the AVD detects ways of steath/infection not used by virusses yet.
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

