@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node Functies "The arguments seen from the sky"
The different tests can also be  selected by using arguments. Every
function has its own letter. By using these letters in the argument the
test selected will be performed. There is no specific order for the
letters and you may use capitals if you like...

The @{"Resident Check" LINK Resident} is always performed. This check tests the system for
resident structures and alike.

A table showing the tests and the letters:

		@{b}b@{ub} - @{" Bootblock        " LINK Bootblock} @{i}only with bootblock.library@{ui}
		@{b}d@{ub} - @{" Device checksum  " LINK DevTest}
		@{b}e@{ub} - @{" CPU-exception    " LINK ExcepTest}
		@{b}i@{ub} - @{" Interupt         " LINK SoftRupts }
		@{b}j@{ub} - @{" JMP-Patches      " LINK Patch } @{i}only with recogpatch.library@{ui}
		@{b}k@{ub} - @{" Keyboard.device  " LINK KeyBoard} @{i}only >KS2.0@{ui}
		@{b}l@{ub} - @{" Library checksum " LINK LibTest}
		@{b}p@{ub} - @{" Enlarge window   " LINK PAL}
		@{b}t@{ub} - @{" ROM-Tags         " LINK TagTest}
		@{b}v@{ub} - @{" Disk-Validators  " LINK Validator} @{i}all disks@{ui}
		@{b}-@{ub} - @{" Ignore Gui-prefs " LINK Minus} @{i}made with AVD-Gui@{ui}
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node AVD-Gui "AVD-Gui, the AVD configuration tool"
The @{"AVD" LINK Main} can be configured by using the AVD-Gui. By checking the boxes
an AVD-test is switched on. When a box is not checked, the test is
switched off.

When the AVD is started from the shell or CLI, @{"arguments" LINK FUncties} can be passed
to specify tests to be performed. The tests specified by the AVD-Gui
are added to the tests specified by the arguments. By using the minus
sign in the argument, only the tests specified in the argument are
performed, the Gui prefs will be ignored.

The next test are found in the AVD-Gui window:

	@{" Bootblocks       " LINK Bootblock}	@{" ROM-Tags         " LINK TagTest}
	@{" Disk-Validators  " LINK Validator}	@{" Exception        " LINK ExcepTest}
				@{" Interupts        " LINK SoftRupts }
	@{" Device checksum  " LINK DevTest}	@{" Keyboard handler " LINK KeyBoard}
	@{" Library patches  " LINK Patch }
	@{" Library checksum " LINK LibTest}	@{" Enlarge window   " LINK PAL}

When the right tests are selected the "Save" button may be used to
store the newly made configuration. When the "Use" button is selected
the new configuration will be used until the next reboot. By using
the "Cancel" button the new configuration will be discarded and the
old will remain in place.

If the option "Bootblocks" is disabled, the "bootblock.library" is
missing. If the option "Library patches" is disabled, the recogpatch.library
is missing.
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node Resident "The AVD resident check"
Some older virusses made itself resident, thus they were capable to
do their trick even if the user reset the system.
To be resident the virusses have to change some standard pointers in
the system. Almost every viruskiller nowadays manages to detect such
a resident piece of code.

Beside these resident-pointers some other strategic places are checked
during the resident check.

This test is always performed (except for the ? argument).

Virusses of younger generation do not use resident code anymore since
they will be detected very soon. Writers of these virusses must find
other ways to stay in memory after a reset.

When something resident is found, an @{"AlarmWindow" LINK Alarm_Window} is opened.
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node Alarm_Window "The AVD AlarmWindow"
The alarm-window consist of five parts: The name of the window, a piece of
memory, the base address of this memory, the slider at the right of the
memory and the gadgets.

The name of the window reveals some information about the thing found.
e.g. If there is an corrupt disk-validator or which resident pointer
was corrupted.

The largest part of the window is used for the memory HEX-dump. The 
contents of this dump is information related to the "problem" found.
When an illigal disk-validator was found, the memory-dump is from the
illigal validator, when an illegal pointer waas found, the dump is made
of the code to which the pointer pointed.

The base adress is the first character in the top of the window when the
window was opened. This address may be used to start a real memory
monitor or an disassembler to check the memory real out.
The slider at the right is used to expand the view. You are able to scroll
the HEX-dump up and down to see more of the memory.

Beneath the window there are two gadgets. The gadget to the right is
called "Do nothing" and clicking it will close the window. The AVD will
continue it's search. The gadget to the left is called "Cold Reset" and
it will reset your system in a very rude way. No virus will survive.

Since it is not funny to click "Do nothing" a hundred times when you
started some large patch, it is possible the cancel the complete test
by clicking the close gadget on the window.
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node Validator "The AVD Validator Test"
The option "v" makes the AVD check the Disk-Validators on the disks in
all connected drives (including hard-disks).
During the test the AVD displays the names of all Validators found (and
thus the Validators tested). When a Validator appears on a disk where
it never was (and shouldn't be), something stinks...

When a currupt Disk-Validator is found an @{"AlarmWindow" LINK Alarm_Window} is opened.

@{i}@{b}WARNING:@{ub}

NEVER delete a corrupt Disk-Validator by hand! Some Validator-virusses
encrypt parts of the disk. These parts can only be rescued by a decent
viruskiller! So: always use a viruskiller to remove virusses!!@{ui}
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node DosTest "The AVD dos.library test (debug function)"
The option "-d" used to start the dos.library test.

		@{b}Removed since AVD V1.9.0@{ub}
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node ExecTest "The AVD exec.library test (debug function)"
The option "-e" used to start the exec.library test.

		@{b}Removed since AVD V1.9.0@{ub}
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node Bootblock "The AVD Bootblock Test"
The option "b" makes the AVD check the bootblock of the disks in all
floppy diskdrives.

The bootblock was the place where the first Amiga virus was made for.
Since then many followed. This type of virus is very old and hence
there are many tools to detect (and remove) this kind of virus.
And also: this type of virus is unable to infect a harddisk in the
same way. The bootblock on a harddisk is not executed as is done
with the bootblock on a diskette.

Although the AVD is "shipped" with a bootblock test. With the help of
the AVD the checking of bootblocks is done automagically. When a (old?)
disk is in the drive and it contains a bootblock virus, it will be
discovered. Checking the bootblock doesn't take much extra time, but
it gives extra protection.

A second reasen for implementing was the simple way it is implemented.
This thanks to Johan Eliasson, member of Safe Hex International (SHI),
an organisation grounded to force computer virusses to the pages of
history. Johan Eliasson wrote the Bootblock.library which is used (and
included) by the AVD. The Bootblock.library recognises hundreds of
virusses using a "brainfile". By updating this brainfile you always
have the latest protection.

Unknown bootblocks are displayd using an @{"AlarmWindow" LINK Alarm_Window}.
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node ExcepTest "The AVD Exception Test"
The option "e" makes the AVD check the exeption vectors of the CPU.

The microprocessors of Motorolas 68000 family use a list with vectors.
When something in the system goes wrong, one of the vectors is used to
start the right system code (mostly a "Software failure" requester...).

A virus may change such an vector. By producing a fault condition, the
virus may call itself. There are many ways for virusses to use this
technique to infect the system.

The exeption test examines the vectors and checks if they point to
the addresses in ROM, or just to some (suspicious) software in RAM.
When vectors are suspected, an @{"AlarmWindow" LINK Alarm_Window} is opened to show the code
of the routine where the vector is pointing to.
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node KeyBoard "The AVD KeyBoard.device Test"
The option "k" makes the AVD check the keyboard.device for reset
handlers.

Since KickStart 1.2 the possibility exists to make a resethandler
using the keyboard device. This handler should be called at the moment
the system is being reset. This did not work since the system was
reset via the hardware: the system rebooted before it could even
reach the handler...

The A1200 and the A4000 wait approximately 10 seconds before reset.
This to allow the reset-handlers to do their job. When the last handler
is ready, the machine resets, or when 10 seconds elapsed since the
reset was invoked.

Virusses can do nice tricks with these kinds of functions.

The keyBoard.device test checks for resethandlers which are installed
in RAM. Suspicious handlers are shown using an @{"AlarmWindow" LINK Alarm_Window}.
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node SoftRupts "The AVD software interrupt test"
The option "i" makes the AVD check the software interrupts.

It is possible (even on the oldest Amiga) to make a virus resident
using a software interrupt. It was even possible to catch a coldreset
using an interrupt. (The AVD coldreset can't be catched!).

A suspicios interrupt is displayed using an @{"AlarmWindow" LINK Alarm_Window}. Normally
users of KS1.3 and below get AlarmWindows when there is nothing wrong
in their system. This is since the KS1.3 system used software interrupts
in RAM. Systems of higher versions do not have such interrupts (unless
they were patched by SetPatch offcourse..)

Also there are applications installing an own software interrupt (and
why not?). An example of such an application is Deluxe Paint(TM) or
the HCMenu. To give the user an extra indication the name of the
interrupt is diplayed in the drag-bar of the AlarmWindow.


@{i}@{b}NOTE:@{ub}	Mr. MVA warned me that his GVP HD-controller in-
	stalled an interrupt during the boot. Since this interrupt is not
	standard, the AVD will open an Alarm-Window.
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node Patch "The JMP-Patch Test."
The optie "j" makes the AVD check the Library JMP tables for patches.

Every library is a collection of functions for a certain purpose. In
the dos.library all kinds of functions meant for data storage are
found.
To make these functions accesible by other applications a JMP table
is used. This is a table with the addresses of the functions.
By changing an address in the table it is possible to replace a
function in the library by an other function. Such an other function
is called a "patch".

A patch may be good or evil: Commodore uses the system of patches
to remove bugs in the operating system and replace them by better
code.

BUT a patch can also be a virus. By replacing system routines for
infection routines a virus can spread itself, and that is less fun...

By checking if all JMP-table addresses are in ROM all patches will
be found (they can't be in ROM). But since not all patches are virusses
this is not a very smart test. When a patch is found it must be
checked if it is a good patch or if it is evil.

This is done by the recogpatch.library made by M de Reuver. With the help
of this library patches are tested. The library contains of a database
which is filled with "good" patches. When a patch is found, and it is
in the database, then the patch is good and no problem. When the patch
is NOT in the database there are two options: the patch is good but not
known by the recogpatch.library, or the patch is a virus...

When unknown pathces are found the @{"alarmwindow" LINK Alarm_Window} pops up and shows
information about the patch (lib name, offset, address etc).
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node LibTest "The Library Test."
The option "l" makes the AVD check the libraries.

Every library is equipped with a checksum. When the library is tampered
by a virus the checksum will be wrong. This test checks all the sums
of all libraries loaded. Offcourse: when a virus makes sure that the
checksum is allright nothing will be found!

Not only the checksum is tested: the complete JMP-table of every
library is checked. Some virusses exchange the JMP's for other in-
structions. They will be found.

When something is found, an @{"alarmwindow" LINK Alarm_Window} appears. Information is given
about the library and it's wrong checksum, or which JMP-node was exchanged
for other instructions.

@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node DevTest "The Device Test."
The option "d" makes the AVD check the devices.

This test is simular to the @{ "Library Test" LINK LibTest}, but it test devices instead
of libraries. Therefore this test is called the "Device Test" and not
"library test". When this test was called "library test" also, it did
not only have a wrong name, both test would be difficult te recognise...

Older versions of the AVD used one option to test both the libraries and
the devices. Since it is difficut to thing right, KS3.0 uses a wrong
ROM checksum for the "carddisk.device", which gave a false alarm on the
AVD on my system.
By splitting the tests, I still am able to use the library test, but I
cannot use the device test. I can't get very happy with this...
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node TagTest "The ROMTag test."
The option "t" makes the AVD check the ROM-Tags.

During system boot the Amiga uses a list with pointers to resident
software. This software is located in ROM. The first A1000's had no
ROM. To make the kickstart (loaded from disk) resident although it is
possible to exted this list with software in RAM. This is already
tested with the @{"Resident Check" LINK Resident}.

After a while it showed to be possible to set the values for this list
a split-second before reset (using an interrupt). In that way the virus
is ahead of the detector. To find this kind of code the @{"softinterrupt Test" LINK SoftRupts}
was implemented in the AVD.

Probably there will be enough ways to do the same, but without the use
of the interrupts. Now. Every piece of software surviving a reset can
be found after the reset. The ROM-Tag test is used to test the system
for survivors after the reset.

Survivors are showed publicly using an @{"alarmwindow" LINK Alarm_Window}.
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node PAL "The window enlargement routine."
The option "p" makes the active window as large as it's screen.

To smoothen the multitasking the screenbar is made completely free.
When a user uses a large screenfont this is also incalculated by the
AVD, making the complete screenbar visible.

Example: The system uses a Topaz font (size 8). The screen is 640x256.
	 Now the window coordinates are (0,11) and it's size is 640x245.

Before the the window is changed, it will be checked first. When a
window has size-gadgets it is changed and otherwise not.


@{i}@{b}PS:@{ub}

Users of KS3.0 systems have the luck that Commodore payed more attention
to the PAL useres. PAL systems now boot with 256 line windows.
Since I always have something to complain: I prefer my own PAL routine
since it leaves the screenbar visible. I *NEVER* close the AmigaDOS
boot window since I use *NEXT TO NEVER* WorkBench.@{ui}
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node Minus "Ignoring the AVD-Gui settings."
The AVD is shipped with a real GUI (Graphical User Interface). With the
help of this tool called @{"AVD-Gui" LINK AVD-Gui} the AVD can be configured.

The configuration selected is stored in the "AVD/AVD.Args" file in the
ENV: and ENVARC: directories.

When the AVD is started from CLI or Shell the contents of the prefs file
are added to the @{"arguments" LINK Functies} passed. When only the tests from the arguments
should be performed the minus sign should be added to the arguments. This
makes the AVD to ignore the settings made with the AVD-Gui.
@EndNode

